---
import DocsLayout from '../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';

const sections = [
  { label: 'Why Bedrock', href: '#why-bedrock' },
  { label: 'Proven at Scale', href: '#proven-at-scale' },
  { label: 'The Headliners', href: '#the-headliners' },
  { label: 'The Full Toolkit', href: '#the-full-toolkit' },
  { label: 'Designed in Layers', href: '#designed-in-layers' },
  { label: 'Built to Grow', href: '#built-to-grow' },
  { label: 'Start Building', href: '#start-building' }
];
---

<DocsLayout
  title="sf-bedrock — enterprise Apex that stays readable"
  description="sf-bedrock is a Salesforce architecture toolkit: background jobs that scale, untyped-JSON handling, database-free tests, and dependency injection — forged in a Fortune 100 org with millions of records."
  eyebrow="Salesforce Architecture Toolkit"
  sections={sections}
>
  <Fragment slot="header">
    <h1>Apex that scales without the ceremony.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      sf-bedrock is a foundation for enterprise Apex: background work that drains
      thousands of records safely, unit tests that never touch the database, and
      dependency-injection seams that keep production code direct. It protects
      high-volume orgs without making everyday code heavy. And it reads the way
      the engineer who owns it would write it.
    </p>
    <div class="pill-row" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">
      <span class="pill">Scalable Async</span>
      <span class="pill">Tame Untyped JSON</span>
      <span class="pill">Dependency Injection</span>
      <span class="pill">Human-Maintainable</span>
    </div>
    <div class="pill-row" style="margin-top: 1.5rem; gap: 0.6rem;">
      <a class="button button-primary" href="/getting-started">Get Started</a>
      <a class="button button-secondary" href="/async">Explore the API</a>
    </div>
  </Fragment>

  <section class="doc-section" id="why-bedrock">
    <h2>Why Bedrock</h2>
    <p>
      Enterprise Salesforce usually forces a trade: heavy frameworks that make
      code testable but obscure, or lean code that reads well until the test
      suite grinds against the database and the first big data volume breaks a
      trigger. Bedrock takes neither side. It is a small set of focused tools and
      dependency-injection seams that keep production code direct, keep tests
      fast, and keep automation inside platform limits. It does all of that
      without rewriting how your team already works.
    </p>
    <div class="doc-grid">
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Tests without a database</h3>
        <p>
          Mock DML, SOQL, and cache so unit tests never touch the database.
          Suites that took minutes finish in seconds.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Safe at real volume</h3>
        <p>
          Background work that drains thousands of records in governor-safe
          batches, grouped upserts, and recursion-minded triggers.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Readable by humans</h3>
        <p>
          Minimalist, low-ceremony Apex. The seams live in your tests, not
          tangled through your business logic.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Composable, not monolithic</h3>
        <p>
          Adopt one tool or all of them. Each stands on its own and composes with
          the rest — none takes over your architecture.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="proven-at-scale">
    <h2>Proven at Scale</h2>
    <p>
      These patterns were forged in one of the largest Salesforce orgs on the
      planet: a Fortune 100 environment with millions of records and thousands of
      daily users. There is no tolerance for flaky deploys or runaway governor
      limits. Recursive triggers, exhausted queueable slots, and tests that depend
      on org data are daily realities there, not edge cases. Bedrock is what held
      up under that pressure, distilled and packaged so any team can adopt it.
    </p>
    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Developer-first, by design</strong>
      <p>
        The goal is automation that protects the org and still makes sense to the
        people who own it. Every abstraction earns its place — if it makes
        everyday work heavier, it does not ship.
      </p>
    </div>
    <ul class="token-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Built for scale</strong>
        <span>Shaped by orgs with millions of records and unforgiving daily volume.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tests that mean something</strong>
        <span>Assertions prove real behavior and mutations, not just coverage.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Org-protective</strong>
        <span>Designed to stay inside platform limits, not race against them.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="the-headliners">
    <h2>The Headliners</h2>
    <p>
      Four tools carry most of Bedrock's day-to-day value. Start here — each is
      documented with the contract, real examples, and the testing path.
    </p>
    <div class="doc-grid">
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3><a href="/async">Async</a></h3>
        <p>
          Hand the framework a set of record Ids and it drains them in the
          background, in governor-safe batches, chaining job to job until the
          queue is empty. Every work item is tracked to success or error. Process
          thousands of records without ever tripping the 50-job limit.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3><a href="/generic">Generic</a></h3>
        <p>
          Tame untyped JSON and integration payloads: read and write deeply
          nested values by path, coerce them to the Apex type you ask for, and
          convert cleanly to a typed SObject. No tree of manual casts and
          <code>containsKey</code> checks.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3><a href="/test-data">TestData</a></h3>
        <p>
          A fluent builder for in-memory records — including fields the normal
          constructor rejects, like formula, audit, and Id fields. Realistic test
          data with mock Ids and parent relationships, with zero DML or setup
          bloat.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3><a href="/dml">Dependency Injection</a></h3>
        <p>
          Route every write through <a href="/dml">DML</a> and every read through
          <a href="/query">Query</a>. Production runs the real thing. Tests swap
          in a mock and assert exactly what would have been written or read — no
          database, no <code>SeeAllData</code>.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="the-full-toolkit">
    <h2>The Full Toolkit</h2>
    <p>
      Around the headliners sits a focused supporting cast — each one small,
      single-purpose, and testable.
    </p>
    <ul class="token-list">
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/platform-cache">PlatformCache</a></strong>
        <span>Org and session Platform Cache behind a mockable seam — the part of the platform that is notoriously hard to test, finally testable.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/record-buffer">RecordBuffer</a></strong>
        <span>Stage inserts and updates across a transaction, then flush grouped, deduplicated upserts at a controlled point.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/trigger-handler">TriggerHandler</a></strong>
        <span>Context detection and dispatch handled; you override only the before/after hooks that matter.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/feature-flag">FeatureFlag</a></strong>
        <span>Metadata-driven toggles that fail closed, with one-line overrides for tests.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/pluck">Pluck</a></strong>
        <span>Turn a list of records into a deduped <code>Set&lt;Id&gt;</code> in one call — the small helper that feeds list-driven APIs like Async.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="designed-in-layers">
    <h2>Designed in Layers</h2>
    <p>
      Separation of concerns is the organizing principle. Bedrock gives each
      layer a home so logic stops leaking across boundaries — and so the next
      engineer can find it where they expect.
    </p>
    <ul class="token-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Schema</strong>
        <span>SObjects, metadata, and settings that define the system's shape.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Domain</strong>
        <span>Triggers and record lifecycle behavior, coordinated by small handlers.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Selector</strong>
        <span>Reusable, testable query logic built on Query.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Service</strong>
        <span>Cross-record orchestration and the business behavior that matters.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>UI Layer</strong>
        <span>Components and thin controllers that adapt to the glass and delegate complexity to services.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="built-to-grow">
    <h2>Built to Grow</h2>
    <p>
      The foundation ships today. The roadmap extends the same approach into
      query encapsulation and a shared async foundation — delivered one
      deliberate, inspectable piece at a time, never as a speculative
      megaframework.
    </p>
    <div class="pill-row">
      <span class="pill">Selector</span>
      <span class="pill">Selector.Cached</span>
      <span class="pill">Event</span>
      <span class="pill">Scheduler</span>
      <span class="pill">LimitsService</span>
    </div>
    <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">
      Async, Event, and Scheduler will share one foundation while keeping
      separate execution pools. Each consults a limit-aware service before
      running work, so framework automation protects org health instead of
      threatening it.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="start-building">
    <h2>Start Building</h2>
    <p>
      Stand up the docs locally, then start with the testing foundation —
      <code>TestData</code>, <code>DML</code>, and <code>Query</code> — and feel
      how fast a Bedrock test suite runs. When you are ready to move real volume,
      reach for <code>Async</code>.
    </p>
    <div class="utility-panel">
      <div>
        <h3>Ready in minutes</h3>
        <p>
          Begin with the getting-started guide, or jump straight into the API
          that anchors every Bedrock test.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="pill-row" style="gap: 0.6rem;">
        <a class="button button-primary" href="/getting-started">Getting Started</a>
        <a class="button button-secondary" href="/test-data">TestData API</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
